speech.p:
The hon. Gentleman referred to television, not terrorism. If there had not been such shouting—I bet there would not be such shouting if the cameras were here—I might have heard. We have been asked whether the House would be as noisy if we had television cameras;

and I am sure that if they were here the new entrants at the door would be listening in rapt attention. Television would quieten this House.

I beg the House to vote for a controlled experiment — it would be under the control of the House—to enable the Select Committee to report its findings to the House. We shall not be voting for a change that will last for all time. We shall be voting for this House to put its mind to change instead of talking about it. Let us stop talking—let us do something.
